description._content: To British eyes, US urban zoning like this looks bizarre. The foreground comprises residential streets of three-storey houses with the characteristic San Francisco bay windows (themselves reminiscent of British 20th Century suburban architecture), blending into a narrow band of two-storey office buildings. Then, as abruptly as crossing Washington Street, there rises a wall of high-rise towers including the 48-storey Transamerica Pyramid. Designed by William Pereira & Associates and built 1969-72 for the Transamerica Corporation, the distinctive 260m-tall Transamerica Pyramid was once ranked amongst the world's five tallest buildings; it's now 'merely' the tallest in San Francisco, clearly visible from across the region. It was nearly the world's second tallest, at 305 m (1,000 feet), but the City's Planning Commission was concerned about the view from Nob Hill, off the right of the image. Planning concerns also inspired its tapered shape, which reduces the building's apparent shadow and allows more light to penetrate to street level. The 'wings' rising from the 29th floor accommodate unavoidably vertical elements of the building: two elevator shafts on the east, and a stairwell and a smoke tower on the west. To the immediate right of the Pyramid is Montgomery Street, the original heart of the Financial District and "the Wall Street of the West". As recently as 1830 it was the waterfront, at which ships were able to moor; everything to the left is reclaimed land. Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in the 19th Century; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s. photo.title: Giant Victory

description._content: This one is a bit of an oldie that I somehow forgot about marinating in the archives. About a year ago, Alan and I made our way here in hopes of shooting the SF blue hour skyline. It was World Series game 4 and hence the skyline was bathed in orange trim, complete with an orange Transamerica beacon. While waiting for the sun to set, the unexpected happened. Marine fog began a push into the bay covering up large portions of downtown San Francisco. We had envisioned mostly clear skies to catch the twilight colors and a crisp view of the city lights below. The fog seemed to throw a whole new twist to things as half our scene became engulfed in the fog. Just as we thought it would be skunk city, the fickle fog began to retreat. The retreat coincided with sunset as all the conditions came together for this shot: high clouds lighting up, low fog, orange Coit Tower, orange Transamerica beacon, and the downtown skyline with orange trim. Sometimes, Mother Nature throws us a curveball that ends up being for the better. Canon 5D Mark II EF 24-70mm f/2.8L II Website | Facebook | Google+

photo.title: Tripping the Bay

description._content: Photographing this view including city lights was not the only image I wanted to capture. Panorama and long exposure photography was also part of the plan. Due to the orientation of the sun, I knew that I would have a better chance of good light during the early morning hours. After shooting a few long exposures just before sunrise, it was now time for the sun to light up part of the city, and I could concentrate my efforts on a panorama image. I waited for different parts of the scene to become illuminated, and then took fourteen separate exposures. Pre-visualizing the shot, I had already attached a Singh-Ray Blue-Gold Intensifying filter to my lens. This was the extra ingredient needed to help enhance the areas of bright sunlight. All images were photographed at an aperture of f/8. I find that it is critical to keep a constant aperture when shooting panoramic photography. A shutter speed of 1/13 second was used to shoot all images except one. Website: www.davidshieldphotography.com

First two attempts were in last summer, 1st time i got stuck in traffic(it takes more than hour drive from my place) and lost that blue hour. 2nd time that place was taken( you can get this shot only from one spot, where Golden gate bridge & Transamerica pyramid are perfectly aligned), but on that day  i realized how windy & cold this place can get. I needed really sturdy tripod to get this shot. So this holiday season i got my new tripod & ball-head combo & tried them for the first time for this shot. 
As they say try, try & try ! 
Single Exposure, single shot, no HDR
Taken with Nikon - D610, Nikkor 70-200 VRII-2.8g, @ 180mm, f8, 30sec

photo.title: Trouble in paradise

description._content:
Got a chance to test out the new Sony A7R + Metabones Smart Adapter III + 17 TS-E. The A7R has performed quite well up until now, but it appears the combo flares badly if there are bright lights just outside of frame.

After some investigating, it appears that stray light from the 17 TS-E's large image circle will bounce off the ribbed inner surface of the Metabones Smart Adapter III, causing a blooming effect.  You can easily replicate this by framing a shot that flares at the edge, then unmounting the camera from the adapter while it is still on the tripod (being careful not to disturb the framing of the lens).  If you look straight through the adapter, you should find a bright spot inside the adapter opposite the direction of the lightsource.  Im not sure why Metabones did not design a wider optical path or use a more light absorbent material like the black velvet in most lens or teleconverters.

Its not a showstopper since the problem is visible in liveview and you can just reframe slightly or blocking it with your hand.  However it might be time to start looking for a true FF adapter... or a native F-E mount UWA....

(4 second exposure)

description._content: One of San Francisco's most famous views can be found in Alamo Square overlooking the Victorian Row houses now known as the "Painted Ladies". The houses were built between 1892 and 1896. One of the houses was put on the market for $4 million in 2010, though it did not sell even after reduction to a paltry $3 million. One of them did sell in 2001 for $1.25 million. On November 19th, 2013, the neighborhood voted to ban tour buses with ten or more seats from the surrounding area. I suppose it must be annoying to have so many tourists taking a picture of your front door.

photo.title: American West

description._content: The last daylight over the San Francisco cityscape. This is part of the view while ascending Telegraph Hill in San Francisco. Most of the hillside is lined with houses up to the top, but there are a few side spots like this where you can find a spot to capture a relatively unobstructed view of the city. I decided to shoot this as a 4 part panorama, which can sometimes be tricky to pull off handheld. In this case, I was able to line everything up great and correct inconsistencies without issue. I've found that the tricky part of editing a shot like this isn't so much merging the panorama, but correcting for distortion. I generally like to use the warp tool in photoshop to handle lens distortion and horizon shifts (especially now that the warp tool can be used non-desctructively), but that process becomes much more difficult when there are so many vertical lines to keep straight. It's not impossible, just time consuming. After I finished the warp process, the finishing the rest of the photo was fun and quick. View on Tumblr

description._content:
This is a 1.1 gigapixel (15,000h x 75,000w, 1x5 ratio) view of San Francisco reduced to 10% of its original width and height.  It 
was created from 100, 11-20-second exposures with the 21 megapixel Canon 5D MKII, and a Canon 400L 5.6 lens.  The photos 
were taken just after sunset from the Marin Headlands on several different evenings under similar lighting conditions.  

All of this effort was required to produce an image that would appear to be taken during that 10-minute period that happens 
about 20 minutes after sunset when the fading daylight and the city lights reach equilibrium.  This could easily be printed at 34ft 
wide by 6 ft tall (200dpi) with fine resolution with little to no pixelation or noise visible at a viewing distance of 1 foot!

I used AutoPano stitching software at first, however as with the other panorama, it (and other stitchers) became hopelessly 
confused by the numerous bridge cables since one looks like another.  So most of this image was hand stitched by me in 
Photoshop.  Also, I did not use a Gigapan machine or a tripod, I used a plastic bucket, a x-large pizza-sized plywood round and 
some wood shims.  This was far more stable than a tripod in the wind with a huge lens, and easier to level and pan across.

Please contact me, Patrick Smith, at patrick @ patricksmithphotography.com with any questions.  The 2.5 gigabyte 8-bit psb file is 
for sale starting at US $4,995.00 for the 34 foot version with lower prices for smaller files.  There are places that will print files of 
this size!

description._content:
The slow dismantling of the old East Span of the Bay Bridge. 

Standing in the shadow of its newer, sleeker, and more beautiful sister, it's a part of history that we're seeing come apart right before our very eyes. Slowly, sections of the bridge are being dismantled, as great care is being taken to consider the environmental impact of both the Bay and the host/species of birds that nested in the old framework.

It has provided service to millions over the years, but now its time has come and is about to go.

Edited with Aviary using Dean for the effects.

photo.title: Architectural Contrast in San Francisco

description._content:
The majestic flatiron Sentinal Building, a historic landmark in the heart of North Beach, stands in stark contrast to the Transamerica Pyramid.  The "Transamerica Pyramid", no longer owned by the Transamerica Corporation, is the tallest and most recognizable skyscraper in San Francisco.  Currently ranked as the 105th tallest building in the world, it has a height of 853 ft. 

Construction of the Sentinal Building, also known as Columbus Tower, began prior to the 'Great Earthquake' of 1906 but was delayed as a result of that event and not completed until 1907.  It originally housed the headquarters of the notorious Abe Ruef (1864-1936), a local political figure of the time, and also featured the famous restaurant 'Caesar's' (on the ground floor) that was widely credited as the creator of the popular Caesar's Salad.  The Kingston Trio once owned the building and used it as their headquarters during the 1960's.  In the 1970's the building was purchased by film director, Francis Ford Coppola ("The Godfather"), who renovated it into what we see today.  He set up his studio, American Zoetrope, there and, in 1999, opened Cafe Zoetrope, a bistro and wine shop satellite of his Inglenook Estate Winery in the Napa Valley.

description._content: On a crisp and clear morning, the view from Russian Hill towards the Bay, sweeping from downtown San Francisco around to Coit Tower was simply stunning. To more fully enjoy the panoramic experience, I highly recommend that you look at this panorama on the Dermandar website, where you can zoom and pan your way around the scene. Try the full screen mode to fully immerse yourself in the scene (just select the arrow in the top right of the image). www.dermandar.com/p/cpVCli/russian-hill-san-francisco-201... Various other links ... www.transamericapyramidcenter.com/ baybridgeinfo.org/ en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coit_Tower en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ina_Coolbrith sfrecpark.org/destination/ina-coolbrith-park/ The photographs for this panorama were taken looking east from Ina Coolbrith Park next to Vallejo Street, between Mason and Taylor Streets. San Francisco, California, USA. (N.B. Great care was required in the choice of apps used to process this panorama - I ensured that I only used those apps that could process and retain the size of large images.) iPhone 5s - Photographs taken with the camera on an iPhone 5s. Camera - The native Camera app was used with the HDR option. AutoStitch - The 5 landscape orientation photographs were compiled into a panorama that was 8712 x 3586 pixels in size. Cropped to 7210 x 2666 pixels. Filterstorm - Image straightened. FrontView - A trapezoidal crop was applied to change the apparent perspective. Snapseed - Overall lighting changes were applied. Handy Photo - Retouched some clouds out of the upper right portion of the image. Filterstorm - Cropped the image to 7029 x 2027 pixels. Snapseed - Selective lighting changes applied to darken the sky and also to the foreground in the lower right portion of the image. Filterstorm - A small amount of black vignette added to the image. Noise reduction and sharpening filters applied. Snapseed - Final overall lighting adjustment applied. ExifEditor - EXIF data from one of the original images was transferred to the panorama image. Filterstorm - A series of white, black and white borders were added, taking the image dimensions to 7297 x 2295 pixels. (Filed as 20131218_iPadMiniRetina 261 AutoStitch-Filterstorm-FrontView-Snapseed-HandyPhoto-ExifEditor.JPG)

photo.title: Pier 7

description._content:
Christmastime in San Francisco means lights around the Embarcadero Center and the Beacon on top of the Transamerica building.

I wanted to take a picture with all these lights plus the streetlights of the pier, at blue hour. On a clear evening I went to Pier 7 before sunset and waited. Blue hour took only 5 minutes and I had to share my spot with a French panorama photographer, so with 30 second exposures I could only get a few in. Unfortunately the lights were not cooperating; the beacon came on a bit late and the pier lights were turning on and off randomly (it did not look like they were meant to do that); this is the only picture where only one of the lights is out, they were never all on at the same time.

The 'star' in the middle of the image is actually Venus! A local came over to talk to me to make sure I was aware of that. He seemed relieved that I knew already.

photo.title: Foggy sunrise

description._content: The weather in the San Francisco can change very quickly; in summer, a foggy morning often turns into a completely clear afternoon. On this day however, the fog rolling into the Bay through the Golden Gate was already fairly low after sunrise, only just covering the deck of the Golden Gate bridge (just under the bottom of the frame) but not San Francisco itself. Fun fact: I took this picture one day after this picture; I was lucky to get a morning with perfect fog right after a clear morning. This particular shot is also part of a timelapse to be published in my 'Sunrise in the Bay' video. This is currently still in progress, but a preview can be found here.

description._content: On a particularly clear morning in October I decided to go to the Golden Gate bridge to photograph the sunrise. This is one of my favorite shots, taken just moments before the sun came up. Through the cables of the suspension bridge you can clearly see some of the other San Francisco landmarks, such as the Transamerica Pyramid, Coit Tower and the Bay Bridge which connects San Francisco to Yerba Buena and the East Bay. I also shot a timelapse video of this sunrise, as part of my 'Sunrise in the Bay' video project. A preview can be found here.
